# Security Guidelines

## Input Validation

- Validate ALL user input at the API boundary using FluentValidation
- Never trust client-side validation alone
- Use parameterized queries — EF Core does this by default, but watch raw SQL

```csharp
public class CreateUserValidator : AbstractValidator<CreateUserRequest>
{
    public CreateUserValidator()
    {
        RuleFor(x => x.Email).NotEmpty().EmailAddress().MaximumLength(255);
        RuleFor(x => x.Name).NotEmpty().MaximumLength(100);
        RuleFor(x => x.Role).IsInEnum();
    }
}
```

## Authentication & Authorization

- Use ASP.NET Core Identity or JWT Bearer tokens
- Short-lived access tokens (15 min), long-lived refresh tokens (7 days) stored server-side
- Hash passwords with bcrypt or Argon2id (never MD5/SHA)
- Rate-limit auth endpoints with `AspNetCoreRateLimit` or built-in rate limiter
- Check permissions via `[Authorize(Policy = "...")]` or endpoint filters — not inside handlers

## Secrets

- Never hardcode secrets — use `IConfiguration` with User Secrets / Azure Key Vault
- Never log tokens, passwords, or PII
- Use `IOptions<T>` with validation for typed configuration access
